“It is true we are in a difficult position as a country. We have very serious challenges globally and as a nation," the Deputy President said.
“We have the coronavirus pandemic that has caused a serious economic meltdown and we also have a serious health challenge that has put pressure on our health infrastructure and human capital, hence unrest in that sector, hence the need to help address them,” Ruto went on.





He told Mr Mudavadi, Wiper leader Kalonzo Musyoka, his Ford Kenya counterpart Moses Wetang’ula and ODM leader Raila Odinga to use their access to President Uhuru Kenyatta and provide the needed help to confront the situation.
“This is not time to point fingers but to stand together as a nation to confront this situation together especially now that we are in this space of the 'Handshake' where all of us are talking and working together,” the DP said.
He went on: “Let us be friends and partners when the times are good and even when times are bad. It will not be fair for Musalia, Kalonzo, Weta and Agwambo to speak to the President as I do; it is only fair that we manage this situation together without saying it is you guys.”
He urged the opposition leaders not to abandon the government during difficult times.



